1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6
{ One reason I chose the 3-piece system over others @@StartBracket@@for example over Gelfand variation with 7...Nbd7 without 7...Be7@@EndBracket@@ is the fact that there are a relatively few sidelines for White that are dangerous for us.   That said, it is important to know how to deal with them and you may actually encounter them if you are facing less experienced players, although, what am I saying, I have personally faced one against Magnus Carlsen himself... }
7. f3
{ This has been played by Magnus Carlsen three times and once in a must-win game against me, that I am happy to tell you, I didn't even come close to losing @@StartBracket@@did I play the Najdorf in a must-not-lose? Yes!@@EndBracket@@.   The idea is that White is so desperate to get the English Attack setup against the Scheveningen pawn structure that is the setup with the pawn on e6 and not with e5, that he is ready to waste a move for that and misplace the bishop to g5. In fact, the English Attack with e6 and White's bishop on e3 is also playable for Black, so this system, obviously can't be critical.   Still, White was the first one to begin the game and he can afford some sophistication. Let's see how we respond. }
7... Be7
{ There are many setups and move orders here. Even  7...Nc6!?  or on the next moves is a very viable setup, Black gets to play the Rauzer variation with White having committed to the f3 set up very early, when against many systems he often would have liked to go for the f4 setup.  Besides we can do the setups with b5 and Nbd7 and have a fine version of that too. My main recommendation is to play b5 first and see what happens later, keeping the knight on b8 flexible. }
8. Qd2 b5
{ In the game against Carlsen, I castled first, avoiding a4 just in case, but actually, there is no reason at all to fear it. }
9. a4
{ Black can react here with  9...b4  , as well as  9...bxa4  , both, are fine. }
9... b4 10. Na2 e5 11. Nb3
{ Now the immediate  11...Nxe4  can be met with  12.Qd5!  , so Black has to prepare that first. }
11... Be6
{ As  12.Nxb4  can be met with  12...Nxe4!  to win the b4 pawn White has to part with his bishop. }
12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nxb4 Bg5 14. Qc3 O-O
{ And with White's king struggling to castle and Black having the dominant dark-squared bishop, Black has full compensation here. The plan is to develop the b8 knight to d7 or c6 after some preparation with a6-a5, Qb6/Qd7, and so on. }
