{ The move 6. Be3, nowadays mainly connected with the idea of the English Attack @@StartBracket@@ f3 Qd2 O-O-O setup@@EndBracket@@ is an almost eternal main-line in many Sicilians and the Najdorf is not an exception.   This line is probably the one line that has one way or the other remained in fashion for the past couple of decades. The 6th move trends in the Najdorf comes and goes, but the English Attack enjoys a steady following amongst players of all levels so it is important to be ready to face it.   In this chapter I would like to give an overview of Black's options, before going into details on my recommendation, which I can already assure you is epic. }
6... e5
{ 6...e6  Is the Scheveningen setup, which used to be a favourite of Garry Kasparov for a major period in his career. It leads to crazy variations, though at the top-level a lot of initial Kasparov-romanticism is gone, as the theory has advanced so far that many of the lines go into deep forced endgames and require precise memorization more than creativity and imagination which used to be the case when Kasparov started exploring this territory.   I could have recommended the Scheveningen setups against everything, but for the initial launch of my course, I am convinced it is a better idea to study the fascinating  6...e5  structures first.   6...Ng4  For starters let me explain what this  6...Ng4  is about.  7.Bc1  now Black has to go back to f6, there really is no good alternative. 7.Bg5 is the main move, leading to a big line that is in a fine theoretical shape. One thing, however, is that White can also go back to c1.  7...Nf6  and here there are two issues. First of all if White again plays  8.Be3  and we go  8...Ng4  it is up to him whether to take the draw or play for a win, while we have no way to continue the fight!   Moreover, the English Attack fans can start here with the move @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  and here Black does have to decide to go for  6...e5  or  6...e6  after all.   Now, if you are a fan of the Scheveningen setup against the English attack with  6...e6  the addition of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Ng4  to your repertoire is definitely worth it, as  6.Be3  e6  gives White a ton of dangerous sidelines including  7.g4!?  ,  7.f4  and  7.Be2  and whatnot.   However, if you anyway plan on going  6.f3  e5  then what it basically comes down to, is that all 6.Be3 Ng4 achieves is avoiding some lines like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  e5  7.Nf3   Now we can zoom out further and see the bigger picture. Suppose you play  6.Be2  e6  you allow  7.Be3  which is the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  e6  7.Be2   Also if you want to avoid @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  e5  7.Nb3  Be6  8.h3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h3  e5  7.Nb3  Be6  8.Be3  which is the same thing, you may want to go @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  Ng4  and another 6th move against the 6.h3-system. Very confusing.   Basically, though, in this course I want to recommend the  6...e5  setup whenever possible, which was the favourite setup of Bobby Fischer and the structure I myself find quite fascinating.  So we will play e5 against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  ,  6.f3  ,  6.Be2  and  6.h3  as well and if or when some of them will inter-transpose, we will happily embrace it. This way we don't need 6.Be3 Ng4 in our repertoire. }
7. Nb3
{ In this chapter I will mostly mention the main possibilities against the English Attack, but the another retreat  7.Nf3  is a serious line that we will also have a good look at. Already here Black has a choice to make. I will recommend starting with  7...Be7  because of the sidelines, but against the English Attack setup with  8.f3  it does not matter much how to start and actually, Be6 allows Black even more options, as it delays the development of the f8 bishop. Essentially there are two types of setups, the ones with h7-h5 push stopping g4 push for now and the ones where Black just develops and allows the kingside expansion with g2-g4  @@StartBracket@@and later g4-g5@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Be7
{ 7...Be6  This move has quite some independent value, as there are popular setups with h5 where later the f8 bishop gets developed to g7.  8.f3  This is the English Attack. Lines that have to do with ideas of going f2-f4 instead or h3 instead of f3 are also venomous and we will have a good look at them.  This position can also be reached after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@   6.f3  e5  7.Nb3  Be6  8.Be3  Which is common among those who don't want to allow  6.Be3  Ng4.   8...h5  Similar setup to the one I recommend, but in this move order, White has not yet committed to Qd2, while Black has the flexibility to develop the f8 bishop to g7 later on. There are also setups with 8...Nbd7 without h5 as well, postponing the development of the e7 bishop, but they haven't quite caught on.  9.Nd5   9.Qd2  Is usually met with  9...Nbd7  and if White goes for the O-O-O setup, Black should eventually develop the bishop to e7 and that position will actually also be a part of our repertoire.  9...Bxd5  10.exd5  Nbd7  11.Qd2  g6  Now there are two major setups Be2 O-O and O-O-O. The latter one more fashionable these days.  12.O-O-O  Here another choice for Black. He can go after the d5 pawn with Nb6 or play the somewhat less popular move Bg7, just trying to finish the development. I have played both.  12...Nb6  13.Kb1  Is a pawn sacrifice that became a thing around ten years ago and it remains topical to this day. Black is certainly very fine and there are a lot of games, both over the board and correspondence that one can study here. A very respectable system, but I wanted to offer something fresh and less analyzed for my course, so I went for something slightly different. }
8. f3 Be6 9. Qd2 { Note that g2-g4 is not good here yet because of d5!. } 9...
h5
{ The idea of pushing this pawn only after including Be7 and Qd2 is that after  10.Nd5  Nxd5  11.exd5  Bf5  the move White would want to make,  12.Bd3  is less attractive for White as after  12...Bxd3  13.Qxd3  he had wasted a move on Qd2.   9...O-O  The old and formidable main-line.  10.O-O-O  Nbd7  The alternative 10...a5 used to be popular at some point in time, with the idea that after White goes a4, Black will install a knight on b4 and then break with d6-d5 and crush. However, White has figured out the right move orders there to stop that from happening and the positional weakness of the b5 square on the queenside proved to be a larger factor.  11.g4  b5  12.g5  Here the old main-line is  12...b4  and there is a masterpiece by Vishy Anand against Sergey Karjakin there, perhaps one of the most inspiring Najdorf games of all time, played in 2006. Ever since, White has found some other tries there, though, that is a lot less risky. Nowadays more trendy is the simpler move  12...Nh5  and theory here is growing. This is definitely a fine and reliable line and one that I played myself once, against Peter Leko, who I consider to be one of the greatest English Attack specialists. But again, for practical reasons, I chose to recommend the h5 complex. }
10. Nd5
{ The main and the most principled move. Here I will recommend  10...Nxd5  but I also want to offer an alternative in  10...Bxd5!?  with a very creative but a somewhat dubious idea that I wanted to play against Levon Aronian in a blitz game, which can serve you as a fun surprise weapon for one or two games.   10.O-O-O  White can always play this setup, also against the Be6 h5 system without Be7. We will examine it carefully.   10.Be2  Is a clever idea to stay flexible, that we will also study in great detail. }
