{ The simple setup  10...Be6  11.O-O  Nbd7  followed by Qc7, Rfc8 is perfectly fine too, but the text move is even more principled. }
11. a4
{ After  11.O-O  b5!  Black is doing well. The idea is that after  12.a4  b4  13.Nd5  Nxd5  14.Qxd5  Black has a comfortable move  Rb8  now that the knight has already developed to d7. }
11... Nb6 12. Nd2
{ Trying to prevent Nc4. If  12.O-O  Black has  12...Nc4  sending the bishop back to c1, and then developing comfortably with Be6 and so on. }
12... d5 { A standard positional pawn sacrifice for the dark-squared bishop. }
13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5
{ And now the point is not to regain the pawn on b2, but to fight for the initiative. }
15... f5 16. O-O e4
{ White's queenside pawn majority is quite worthless for now, while Black has beautiful bishops and eventually will start the attack with a well-timed f5-f4! push. }
