{ 6.Bc4 in the Najdorf is a dangerous weapon that Fischer used to employ and it remains popular at the amateur and club level. Contrary to the Fischer-Sozin Attack in the Classical Sicilian where the knight is already on c6 and the pawn is still on a7, Black has a lot more flexibility in his queenside development.   This variation is not seen too much at the high level anymore, but Black should know his move orders not to get into trouble. White's bishop is aimed at the e6 pawn, which is good on one hand, but on the other, as long as the e6 pawn is well defended, the bishop could end up being a bad piece. }
