{ Here White has a lot of different plans. First of all, there are a few ways of dealing with the c4 bishop situation. White can play simply  7.Bb3  or try  7.a4  or  7.a3  ideas to drop the bishop to a2.  White also has a big choice in terms of what to do with his king. The old main-line is to castle short and develop with Qf3, while in the latest high-level games White would more often try to go for English Attack type ideas with Be3 Qe2/Qd2 and O-O-O. }
7. Bg5
{ I don't think I can make sense of this move here. White plays both Bg5 and Bc4 systems in one. If White wants to castle long, then Be3 is a move preferred setup, as the bishop is in the way of the g-pawn.  7.Bb3  b5  8.Bg5  makes a little more sense and will be studiedhere. }
