1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This system used to be played mainly with the idea to pin the knight on c6 and then take it, develop with Nc3 Bg5 and castle long. Nowadays, some top players started playing it with different ideas, like dropping the queen back to e3 and simply finishing the development.   It is not that dangerous, in particular for players who aren't that experienced and want to improve their game, I would recommend, as White, to stay away from such slightly disharmonious systems. That said, as Najdorf players, we are always happy to face these systems, so let's see how to react. }
4... Nc6
{ I had played the  4...Nf6  move order against Carlsen and there are some subtle points there, but it is a lot easier to go for  4...Nc6  , with more clarity and much fewer transpositions.  Now White is choosing from 2 different concepts, the traditional  5.Bb5  and the rare  5.Qe3  which is a very odd-looking setup that has been played a lot at the highest level recently. }
5. Qe3
{ This is very open minded and non standard. White is obviously not worse even after this, thanks to some space advantage and decent pieces, but I don't think that this is something a Sicilian player should be fearing. }
5... g6
{ This or  5...Nf6  first, I don't see the difference. Now White essentially has two different development setups that have been played so far; Bc4 and Be2. There are more move orders, as White can start with Nc3 or h3, but it mostly all transposes to one or the other. }
6. Be2 Bg7
{ The tempting  6...Bh6  doesn't win a piece because of  7.Qc3!  , so we should go for this simple development instead. }
7. O-O Nf6 8. h3
{ Sooner or later White will have to make this useful move, stopping Bg4. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3 Nb4 { A pretty clever regroup. } 10. Qd2
{ The most logical of the options. } 10... b6
{ Intending Bb7, putting pressure on the e4 pawn. } 11. a3 Na6
{ The knight will also pressure the e4 pawn from c5 now. Black has an excellent position. }
