{ This used to be a safe sideline for White, that has always been around at club and amateur level. Who doesn't like to give a check and castle as fast as possible?   But it wasn't until around a decade ago when it was picked up by the leading players, including Magnus Carlsen, that it suddenly became one of the most testing systems against the Najdorf. At first, it brought Black players a lot of problems, but by now slowly the solutions started crystallizing and the Najdorf fans have found various ways to deal with it. }
3... Nd7
{ I am going to recommend  3...Nd7.  To be honest, I think  3...Bd7  is a lot easier and would also take up a lot less space on the course, but I feel that it would be unfair to those who play Najdorf as a fighting weapon and want to get as complicated positions as possible.  3...Nd7  is more in the spirit!   After  3...Bd7  the main-line is  4.Bxd7  when Black again has a choice,  4...Qxd7  is the old main-line when White has two plans the one with c3-d4  5.O-O  Nf6  6.Re1  Nc6  7.c3  e6  8.d4   And the more critical c4 aiming for the Maroczy bind  5.c4  Nf6  6.Nc3  g6  7.d4  etc.   By now Black had figured out various ways of equalizing against it, I would recommend those interested to study the latest games at the highest level.  Another option is  4...Nxd7!?  which had become very popular at the high level recently. There too, White can either go for the centre with the c3-d4 idea or try for a Maroczy bind of sorts. And again, according to the latest high-level games Black holds his own. I for one used the  3...Bd7  4.Bxd7  Nxd7  line twice in a very important blitz tournament and scored 1½ out of 2 by drawing Magnus Carlsen and beating Maxime Vachier Lagrave with it.   Back to  3...Nd7  , White now has a lot of different options. }
4. d4
{ Another major move that has been around for a long time. White goes for some sort of an open Sicilian after all. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ This is the point.  5.Nxd4  would just be a bad version of an open Sicilian Najdorf, when White would have an awkward bishop on b5. Here White centralizes the queen, using the fact that there is no longer the move Nc6 hitting the queen. }
5... a6 6. Be2
{ A fashionable sideline. White keeps the bishop, claims to have misplaced Black's b8 knight and hopes to get a Maroczy bind with c2-c4. }
6... Ngf6 7. c4
{ Allows Black two things, first of all, the g6 setup, which is now very decent, but also a pawn sacrifice that I had prepared a long time ago and once played in a wrong position. }
7... e5 8. Qe3 d5
{ A very spectacular idea. Black gets to develop his initiative very quickly now, as he gets a few tempo moves in. }
9. cxd5 Bc5 10. Qd3 Ng4
{ Suddenly f2 is falling and  11.O-O  can be met with  11...Nxf2!  12.Rxf2  Qb6 }
11. Rf1 { This is the best attempt to do damage control. } 11... Qb6 12. h3
{ The f2 pawn is falling anyway, so White is trying to force the matters. }
12... Nxf2
{ Taking with the bishop  12...Bxf2+  also deserve attention followed by  13.Kd1  Ne3+ }
13. Qc2 f5
{ The knight shouldn't get trapped on f2, so we have to break the stronghold on e4. }
14. Ng5
{ White is trying to control the e4 square, as after exf5 e4! things can get out of hand with White king in the centre. }
14... O-O { Also interesting is  14...Nf6 } 15. Nc3 Nxe4
{ And the position gets simplified. } 16. Ngxe4 fxe4 17. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ Continuing the simplifying line. } 18. Bd2 Bxd2+ 19. Qxd2 Nf6
{ With further trades and equality. } *

