1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin is a relatively popular sideline which is considered to be an easy and a safe way for White to handle all of the Sicilians at once. I must admit, it is indeed very solid and relatively easy for White to learn, but at the same time, it is really very harmless. While White is aiming to build a strong pawn centre with 3.d4, in reality, it is quite the opposite.  With Black to move here, we get the crucial tempo to challenge White's control of the centre. Note, that against Najdorf players White can only play Alapin on the second move.  Against those who play  2.Nf3  e6  or  2.Nf3  Nc6  Sicilian, White can start with  2.Nf3  and only then go  2...--  3.c3  @@StartBracket@@which in fact avoids my recommendation against Alapin!@@EndBracket@@. Against  2.Nf3  d6  however,  3.c3  Nf6  is a different story, as  4.e5  is no longer the same because the e5 square is guarded by our d6 pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ There are two main ways of handling the Alapin, the move I recommend and  2...d5  which is definitely good enough as well. The idea of  2...d5  is that compared to the Scandinavian defence @@StartBracket@@1...d5@@EndBracket@@ the c3 square is no longer available for the knight and so the queen on d5 is feeling majestic. And yes, Scandinavian is not a good opening. }
3. e5 Nd5
{ Here White has a choice from a couple of move orders. In general, there are two main ways of treating this position with White. One is to go for a quick d4 push and another one is to start with Bc4 challenging the d5 knight before pushing the d-pawn. Sometimes these two inter-transpose Black's idea meanwhile is simple, we want to undermine the far advanced e-pawn with d7-d6 break and will pretty much always meet Bc4 with a tempo-retreat Nb6. }
4. d4 { The most often played move. } 4... cxd4
{ It seems simpler to take, though d6 first is also fine. } 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3
d6 7. Nf3 Nc6
