1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The so called Morra-Gambit really doesn't have a point, as we can transpose to Alapin if we want to. It does have a serious following and some people even write books about it, so let's check it out! }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ Taking on d4 with the queen is not great, as we will gain a tempo with Nc6. After  3.Nf3  we can transpose to the Najdorf with  3...d6   We can also think of keeping the pawn after  3.Nf3  with  3...e5!?  as  4.Nxe5  loses to  4...Qa5+ }
3... dxc3
{ The easiest for us is  3...Nf6  which after  4.e5  Nd5  transposes to ourAlapin line, but of course, grabbing the pawn is more principled. }
4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Bc4
{ This is how White usually develops his pieces. Here they usually recommend a6, but there are simpler ways. I like finishing the development first. }
6... Bb4
{ Alternatively,  6...Bc5  is similar, while the main move  6...a6  is something I definitely don't want to recommend. }
7. O-O Nge7 { As far as I can see, Black has pretty easy play here. } 8. Qe2
{ The most often played move. } 8... O-O 9. Rd1 Ng6
{ One of the possibilities, developing the knight to g6 where it sits very comfortably and controls the e5 square. Next we want to develop the c8 bishop with b6 Bb7 or a6-b5. }
10. Bg5 { The most logical. } 10... Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ Black is very comfortable here. } 12. Nb5
{ Here d5 equalizes completely, but we can play more ambitiously. } 12... a6
13. Nd6 b5 14. Bb3 Rb8
{ And we don't care too much about the annoying knight on d6, once we finish our development with Bb7-Ba8. Again, we could go 3...Nf6 or 12...d5 if we are less ambitious. }
